=C2=A0

Lauren: I=E2=80=99m pretty sure I=E2=80=99ve answered this question before,=
 but it=E2=80=99s a perennial one, so I=E2=80=99m happy to revisit it. The =
short answer is that the U.S. does not have the infrastructure to build pur=
e luxury brands=E2=80=94the manufacturing capabilities, the talent
pool, or the history. A proprietor could scoop up a bunch of well-known, al=
l-but-dead American brands=E2=80=94say Geoffrey Beene, Bill Blass, and Will=
i Smith=E2=80=94but even if they attached cool designers and great marketer=
s to each, there is no way to easily scale that without leather goods capab=
ilities, and even then it=E2=80=99s increasingly difficult because of all t=
he competition. When Bernard Arnault hired Marc Jacobs to design Louis Vuit=
ton in the late =E2=80=9990s, LV was already a
pretty big brand. Who knows if it would work now.=C2=A0

