s with wide retail distribution from the jump. I initially reported that re=
tail sales for Lively=E2=80=99s haircare line at Target reached close to $5=
 million in the first three and a half weeks=E2=80=93=E2=80=93and then took=
 a serious hit. I viewed data from two
sources that showed sales dropped by more than 87 percent between August 11=
, their peak, and September 15, which correlates with Justin Baldoni=E2=80=
=99s alleged smear campaign.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

It hasn=E2=80=99t gotten much better since. According to Target sales data =
I viewed, Blake Brown averaged about $191,000 per SKU per week from its Jul=
y 31 launch through Nov 3. But during the four-week period ending November
3, the brand averaged about $93,000 per SKU per week=E2=80=94an enormous de=
cline. A 30 percent drop-off is normal, but a 50 percent drop is something.=
 The dip in sales and change in sentiment regarding Lively and the brand wa=
s unusually extreme. In what felt like days, the narrative around Blake Bro=
wn went from an early success story to people saying they were returning he=
r products. I do wonder if sales will rebound a bit in light of the lawsuit=
 and a number of public figures coming
to Lively=E2=80=99s defense. A person with knowledge of Target=E2=80=99s be=
auty business said a =E2=80=9Chair reset=E2=80=9D at the retailer is immine=
nt, and while probably unrelated, Blakely=E2=80=99s lawsuit is conveniently=
 timed. But ultimately, this person reminded me, beauty brands live and die=
 by their product quality, value, etcetera, so while Lively=E2=80=99s perso=
nal drama may be dominating headlines yet again, it=E2=80=99s the ratings, =
reviews, and repeat purchases that determine long-term success.

=C2=A0

What=E2=80=99s going to happen with price inflation at brands next year? Pl=
ain black ballerina flats can=E2=80=99t possibly get much more expensive!=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Sarah: Well, everything can always get more expensive, but aggressive price=
 increases may finally be cooling off. Consumer packaged goods companies pu=
lled back on price hikes in 2024, and
fashion retail appears to be following suit as customers show clear resista=
nce to paying more. This shift in consumer behavior shows that perhaps bran=
ds have less control in the pricing dynamics at the moment. The luxury resa=
le market continues to grow year over year, giving customers an alternative=
 to owning luxury at sharper price points. Chanel only increased their hand=
bag prices once in 2024. In previous years, the company had traditionally h=
iked prices twice, typically in March and
September.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Globally, brands are diversifying sourcing and production to help combat in=
flation and cost increases. Looking ahead to 2025, we=E2=80=99re likely to =
see more emphasis on accessible price points and value-focused offerings, l=
ike Uniqlo=E2=80=99s sub $100 cashmere. (I=E2=80=99m also excited to explor=
e the Quince of it all in future issues of Line Sheet.) As for whether the =
impending, increasingly probable tariffs
will affect fashion? You won=E2=80=99t see that impact for at least a year =
or two, depending on if and how they are enacted.

=C2=A0

