Do you think Glossier will finally be acquired in
2025?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Rachel: Ah, this was my second-most-asked beauty question over the course o=
f the year, behind only who the next C.E.O. of Est=C3=A9e Lauder will be. (=
St=C3=A9phane de La Faverie officially starts in his new role in six days, =
by the way.) For the better part of a decade, a Glossier sale has been one =
of the most discussed potential acquisitions in the
beauty industry, but interest in the brand=E2=80=99s future has definitely =
peaked the last two-ish years, following some highly publicized =E2=80=9Cgr=
owing pains,=E2=80=9D founder Emily Weiss=E2=80=99s decision to step down a=
s C.E.O., a Sephora rollout, a pretty successful =E2=80=9Cturnaround,=E2=80=
=9D and, most importantly, the engagement of Morgan Stanley to explore sale=
 options.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Sure, an acquisition is always possible,
but Glossier unfortunately came up during a time of tech-level valuations, =
cartoonish fundraises, and prioritizing top-line growth over profitability.=
 Until the brand becomes profitable for real (or can show a viable path to =
meaningful profitability), it=E2=80=99s highly unlikely it will sell for an=
ywhere close to $1.8 billion=E2=80=94its valuation at its last round, in 20=
21. I heard that Glossier=E2=80=99s EBITDA for this year is expected to be =
in the mid-single-digit millions, and about twice that in 2025.
If you do that math, even a best-case scenario=E2=80=93=E2=80=93a 20x multi=
ple on, say, $15 million EBITDA=E2=80=93=E2=80=93would only amount to about=
 a $300 million sale.

Of course, to simply talk of EBITDA and multiples would be oversimplifying =
an extremely nuanced situation and discount the company=E2=80=99s revenue, =
which would be optimized by a strategic (more distribution, lower costs, el=
iminated redundancies, etcetera). Glossier literally invented the millennia=
l beauty playbook, is strong in multiple categories (makeup,
skin, and fragrance), and has proven it can overcome real challenges (evolv=
ing from its D.T.C.-only roots, transitioning from a millennial to Gen Z br=
and, etcetera). I know that the two fragrance launches in September were ve=
ry successful, but we still don=E2=80=99t yet know what re-purchase rates w=
ill look like or how they=E2=80=99ll ultimately impact profitability in 202=
5.

=C2=A0

Sarah, you spent a
good chunk of your career as a buyer at Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s. Is there ev=
en a path to becoming a store buyer-slash-merchant these days?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Sarah: Buying training programs still exist, but they=E2=80=99ve evolved. T=
raditional retail giants have rebranded them as =E2=80=9Cleadership develop=
ment programs,=E2=80=9D where you=E2=80=99ll rotate through different roles=
 before landing as an assistant buyer and eventually a buyer
running a department.

Here=E2=80=99s what I think has really changed: Many aspiring retail execs =
are learning the ropes at direct-to-consumer brands and retail startups. I=
=E2=80=99m sure you=E2=80=99ve heard the popular startup idiom about =E2=80=
=9Cbuilding the plane while you fly it.=E2=80=9D If the startup succeeds (b=
ig if!), you could ride the wave of career growth as it expands. Whether yo=
u choose the structured or startup route, success still boils down to two t=
hings: mastering P&L management
and having that sixth sense for what customers want. Those skills are never=
 going away.

=E2=80=8A

That=E2=80=99s it from Line Sheet this week. R.I.P. bag charms.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

