</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Rachel</em>: This one is complicated. Blake Brown =
Beauty had <em>very </em>strong sales at launch, which is often the case wi=
th celebrity brands, and especially ones with wide retail distribution from=
 the jump. I initially reported that retail sales for Lively=E2=80=99s hair=
care line at Target reached close to $5 million in the first three and a ha=
lf weeks=E2=80=93=E2=80=93and then took a serious hit. I viewed data from t=
wo
sources that showed sales dropped by more than 87 percent between August 11=
, their peak, and September 15, which correlates with <strong>Justin Baldon=
i</strong>=E2=80=99s alleged smear campaign.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It h=
asn=E2=80=99t gotten much better since. According to Target sales data I vi=
ewed, Blake Brown averaged about $191,000 per SKU per week from its July 31=
 launch through Nov 3. But during the four-week period ending November
3, the brand averaged about $93,000 per SKU per week=E2=80=94an enormous de=
cline. A 30 percent drop-off is normal, but a 50 percent drop is <em>someth=
ing</em>. The dip in sales and change in sentiment regarding Lively and the=
 brand was unusually extreme. In what felt like <em>days,</em> the narrativ=
e around Blake Brown went from an early success story to people saying they=
 were returning her products. I do wonder if sales will rebound a bit in li=
ght of the lawsuit and a number of public figures coming
to Lively=E2=80=99s defense. A person with knowledge of Target=E2=80=99s be=
auty business said a =E2=80=9Chair reset=E2=80=9D at the retailer is immine=
nt, and while probably unrelated, Blakely=E2=80=99s lawsuit is conveniently=
 timed. But ultimately, this person reminded me, beauty brands live and die=
 by their product quality, value, etcetera, so while Lively=E2=80=99s perso=
nal drama may be dominating headlines yet again, it=E2=80=99s the ratings, =
reviews, and repeat purchases that determine long-term success.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>What=E2=80=99s going t=
o happen with price inflation at brands next year? Plain black ballerina fl=
ats can=E2=80=99t possibly get much more expensive!=C2=A0</strong></p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;"><em>Sarah</em>: Well, everything <em>can </em>always get more e=
xpensive, but aggressive price increases may finally be cooling off. Consum=
er packaged goods companies pulled back on price hikes in 2024, and
fashion retail appears to be following suit as customers show clear resista=
nce to paying more. This shift in consumer behavior shows that perhaps bran=
ds have less control in the pricing dynamics at the moment. The luxury resa=
le market continues to grow year over year, giving customers an alternative=
 to owning luxury at sharper price points. Chanel only increased their hand=
bag prices once in 2024. In previous years, the company had traditionally h=
iked prices twice, typically in March <em>and</em>
September.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Globally, brands are diversifying sour=
cing and production to help combat inflation and cost increases. Looking ah=
ead to 2025, we=E2=80=99re likely to see more emphasis on accessible price =
points and value-focused offerings, like Uniqlo=E2=80=99s sub $100 cashmere=
=2E (I=E2=80=99m also excited to explore t=
