;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Do you think Glossier will finally=
 be acquired in
2025?=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Rachel</em>: Ah, this was my <=
em>second</em>-most-asked beauty question over the course of the year, behi=
nd only who the next C.E.O. of Est=C3=A9e Lauder will be. (<strong>St=C3=A9=
phane de La Faverie </strong>officially starts in his new role in <em>six</=
em> days, by the way.) For the better part of a decade, a Glossier sale has=
 been one of the most discussed potential acquisitions in the
beauty industry, but interest in the brand=E2=80=99s future has definitely =
peaked the last two-ish years, following some highly publicized =E2=80=9Cgr=
owing pains,=E2=80=9D founder <strong>Emily Weiss</strong>=E2=80=99s decisi=
on to step down as C.E.O., a Sephora rollout, a pretty successful =E2=80=9C=
turnaround,=E2=80=9D and, most importantly, the engagement of Morgan Stanle=
y to explore sale options.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Sure, an acquisition i=
s always <em>possible</em>,
but Glossier unfortunately came up during a time of tech-level valuations, =
cartoonish fundraises, and prioritizing top-line growth over profitability.=
 Until the brand becomes profitable <em>for real</em> (or can show a viable=
 path to meaningful profitability), it=E2=80=99s highly unlikely it will se=
ll for anywhere close to $1.8 billion=E2=80=94its valuation at its last rou=
nd, in 2021. I heard that Glossier=E2=80=99s EBITDA for this year is expect=
ed to be in the mid-single-digit millions, and about twice that in 2025.
If you do that math, even a best-case scenario=E2=80=93=E2=80=93a 20x multi=
ple on, say, $15 million EBITDA=E2=80=93=E2=80=93would only amount to about=
 a $300 million sale. <br/><br/>Of course, to simply talk of EBITDA and mul=
tiples would be oversimplifying an extremely nuanced situation and discount=
 the company=E2=80=99s revenue, which would be optimized by a strategic (mo=
re distribution, lower costs, eliminated redundancies, etcetera). Glossier =
literally invented the millennial beauty playbook, is strong in multiple ca=
tegories (makeup,
skin, <em>and </em>fragrance), and has proven it can overcome real challeng=
es (evolving from its D.T.C.-only roots, transitioning from a millennial to=
 Gen Z brand, etcetera). I know that the two fragrance launches in Septembe=
r were <em>very</em> successful, but we still don=E2=80=99t yet know what r=
e-purchase rates will look like or how they=E2=80=99ll ultimately impact pr=
ofitability in 2025.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0 </p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Sarah, you spent a
good chunk of your career as a buyer at Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s. Is there ev=
en a path to becoming a store buyer-slash-merchant these days?=C2=A0</stron=
g></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Sarah: </em>Buying training programs still exist=
, but they=E2=80=99ve evolved. Traditional retail giants have rebranded the=
m as =E2=80=9Cleadership development programs,=E2=80=9D where you=E2=80=99l=
l rotate through different roles before landing as an assistant buyer and e=
ventually a buyer
running a department.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Here=E2=80=99s what I =
think has really changed: Many aspiring retail execs are learning the ropes=
 at direct-to-consumer brands and retail startups. I=E2=80=99m sure you=E2=
=80=99ve heard the popular startup idiom about =E2=80=9Cbuilding the plane =
while you fly it.=E2=80=9D If the startup succeeds (<em>big if!</em>), you =
could ride the wave of career growth as it expands. Whether you choose the =
structured or startup route, success still boils down to two things: master=
ing P&amp;L management
and having that sixth sense for what customers want. Those skills are never=
 going away.</p></div>
